With no operating system, there is no process, no virtual memory, and no allocator handed to you. SRAM is a single physical region you partition yourself via the **linker script**. Typically `.data`/`.bss` sit at the bottom, the **heap** (if any) grows upward, and the **stack** grows downward from the top of SRAM. Nothing checks the gap between them.

This is why a stack overflow on bare metal is *silent corruption*, not a clean crash: with no MMU, the stack simply overwrites whatever sits below it (your variables, or the heap), and the bug surfaces far away. You size the stack by analysis (worst-case call depth, ISR nesting) and ideally guard it with an MPU region or a watermark pattern.

**Why dynamic allocation is discouraged:** `malloc`/`free` on an MCU is non-deterministic (variable time), fragments a tiny heap until an allocation fails unpredictably, is usually not safe to call from an ISR, and has no recovery path when it returns NULL in the field. The embedded discipline is static allocation: fixed pools, ring buffers, and statically sized buffers whose footprint you can read off the map file.

**There is no `main()` until you write the path to it.** At reset the CPU loads the initial stack pointer from the first vector-table word and the reset handler address from the second, then begins executing the **reset handler / startup code**. That code copies `.data` from its flash load image into SRAM, zeroes `.bss`, optionally sets up the heap and runs C-library/constructor init, and only *then* calls `main`.

```c
void Reset_Handler(void) {
    /* copy .data flash->SRAM, zero .bss, ... */
    extern int main(void);
    main();           /* main() is just another function we chose to call */
    for (;;) { }      /* main must never return on bare metal */
}
```

No runtime did this for you; the startup code and linker script *are* the runtime, and they are yours to understand.
